Defines the JSON report schema for `ctx-verify`'s check runner, tuned to keep passing runs cheap to emit and failing ones fully diagnostic.

Custom `Serialize` impls on `CheckReport` and `Report` (not derived) implement the token-frugal shape: a passing check/run serializes to just `{"status":"pass"}`, omitting `count`/`diagnostics`/`truncated`/`checks` entirely; anything else (`fail`, `errored`, `skipped`) emits the full struct. Changing field names or this collapsing behavior will break whatever consumes the report JSON expecting either the terse or full shape.

`Status` has four variants with a fixed precedence enforced only in `Report::new`: `Errored` > `Fail` > `Skipped` > `Pass` — an infra error outranks a code failure, which outranks a missing tool, so a shrinking toolchain never silently reads as a pass. `Skipped` and `Errored` are distinct from `Fail` by design; the gate fails closed if a tool is missing rather than defaulting to pass.

Key constructors: `CheckReport::skipped(tool: &str)` and `CheckReport::errored(detail: String)` both synthesize a single synthetic `Diagnostic` (file `"<runner>"`, lint `"missing-tool"` or `"exec"`) carrying the reason as a message — neither is ever an empty/silent result. `CheckReport::build(cmd_ok: bool, diagnostics: Vec<Diagnostic>, max: usize)` derives `Status::Fail` if `count > 0 || !cmd_ok`, else `Pass`, and truncates diagnostics to `max`, recording the overflow count in `truncated`. `Report::new(checks: BTreeMap<String, CheckReport>)` computes the aggregate status per the precedence above.